5000|$|CAB was {{the first}} bank {{in the world to}} begin {{operating}} ATMs enabled with <b>iris-recognition</b> <b>technology,</b> which were first deployed in 2006. To date, the iris-recognition ATMs have facilitated over 1.2 million transactions worth $422 million. When the Syrian refugee crisis began, CAB's iris-recognition ATMs were adopted by the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) to disperse financial aid to refugees.|$|E
50|$|As {{with other}} {{photographic}} biometric technologies, iris recognition {{is susceptible to}} poor image quality, with associated failure to enroll rates. As with other identification infrastructure (national residents databases, ID cards, etc.), civil rights activists have voiced concerns that <b>iris-recognition</b> <b>technology</b> might help governments to track individuals beyond their will. Researchers have tricked iris scanners using images generated from digital codes of stored irises. Criminals could exploit this flaw to steal the identities of others.|$|E

